        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="16">
            <title>service procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To prevent personal injury or death, make sure the transmission is in neutral or park, parking
                        brake is set, and wheels are blocked before doing diagnostic or service procedures on engine or
                        vehicle.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Tools Needed:</emph>
            </para>
            <seqlist style="arabic">
                <item>
                    <para>Safety glasses</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Work gloves</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Rivet gun</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>1" putty knife</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Screw drivers Phillips and flat</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Utility knife with a new blade and replacement blades</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Saw Blade; i.e., fine toothed jig saw blade to hand cut plastic</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Cordless drill with &#188;" dia bit and or a Die-grinder (Dremel)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Drill bit .192" - .196" dia.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Tape measure</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Paint Pen Marker, white or Yellow (Not Black)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Duct tape</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Rag or Paper towels</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Flashlight.</para>
                </item>
            </seqlist>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>There is no need to remove the top of the dash.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Place all parts in a safe location for re-assembly.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0890501" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890501.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove instrument cluster bezel by removing 2 screws located underneath left and right
                    sides and pulling from the snap clips top left and right side (Figure 2).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890502" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890502a.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the steering column cover by removing 3 screws from underneath (Figure 3).</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890504" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890504.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 3.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the instrument cluster. Remove 4 screws and disconnect the 3 electrical
                    connectors. Adjust tilt column to ease removal (Figure 4).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890505" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890505a.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="448px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the plastic nipples from the back side of the duct patch part with a utility
                    knife. This will make the surface flush for a better fit (Figure 5).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890507" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890507.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="168px"/>
                <caption>Figure 5.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure and mark the defrost duct for the area that will be cut out (Figure 6).</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890519" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890519a.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="520px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a drill or die grinder (dremel) to follow the cut pattern (Figure 7). Use the saw
                    blade to cut the rest of the perimeter that cannot be cut with the drill or die grinder due to
                    access (Figure 7).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not insert the drill bit further than a 1/4" to avoid drilling a hole in the back side of
                        the duct.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>This can be cut out with out removing the driver side dash cover.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Wear gloves to protect the hands. Wear safety glasses. Tape the end of the saw blade in the
                        location to hold it.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0890509" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890509.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 7.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Once the area is completely cut out, use a utility knife to clean up the edges (Figure
                    8). Trial fit the patch in place (Figure 8). If the patch flanges do not fit flush to the existing
                    duct, use the utility knife to remove the interference.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Patch is gray in color to better identify in the instructions. The kit's patch will be
                        black.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0890510" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890510.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 8.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Drill (4) .192" - .196" dia. holes in locations shown (Figure 9). Make sure to hold the
                    patch so that all flanges set flush to the duct surface by pushing to the right, forward, and down.
                    Be sure the holes are located in the middle of the overlap between the patch flange and the duct.
                    Once one hole is drilled, use the rivets to help hold in place (DO NOT COMPRESS RIVET). Remove
                    rivets and patch.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Only allow the drill bit to penetrate &#188;" through the duct, so that you do not drill a
                        hole in the back side of the duct.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0890511" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890511.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 9.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the plastic shavings out of the defrost duct with a vacuum cleaner (Figure 10).
                    Use duct tape with one end folded up to clean in the hard to reach areas that the vacuum could not
                    reach (Figure 10). Continue to use the duct tape until you get all of the plastic shavings. Also
                    vacuum up the steering area and floor area for general cleaning.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890512" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890512.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 10.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Apply a &#188;" bead of Black Silicone Adhesive sealant around the perimeter, but on the
                    inside of the rivets (Figure 11). Apply a second &#188;" bead around the perimeter and just to the
                    outside of the rivets (Figure 11).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>At the top there may not be enough room for the second bead. That is OK.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0890513" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890513.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 11.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install patch and rivet to the defrost duct (Figure 12).</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890514" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890514.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 12.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Apply a 3rd &#188;" bead of Black Silicone Adhesive sealant around the exterior
                    perimeter and smooth out around perimeter (Figure 13).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890515" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890515.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 13.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The back edge of the patch will be sandwiched between the driver's side dash cover and
                    the defrost duct. That is the intent. This will help hold the patch in place as the adhesive sealer
                    cures (Figure 14).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890516" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890516.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 14.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Re-install the Instrument panel cluster, cluster bevel, and steering column cover
                    (Figure 15) (Reference steps 1 - 3).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890517" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890517.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 15.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Though you will not be able to see the clearance created by the installation of the kit,
                    this is what it looks like with the driver side dash cover off. DO NOT TAKE THE DRIVER SIDE DASH
                    COVER OFF.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0890518" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0890518.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 16.</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the instrument cluster for proper operation and lighting. If the instrument
                    cluster does not operate, doublecheck that all of the connectors were properly connected.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
